    "recap_url": "https://www.goblueraiders.com/news/2026/3/15/baseball-blue-raider-bullpen-holds-late-in-4-3-win-over-kennesaw-state-to-clinch-cusa-series-opener",
    "recap_headline": "Middle Tennessee State University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "MURFREESBORO, Tenn.\u2014\nMiddle Tennessee (12-8, 2-1 CUSA) left-hander\nColin Kerrigan\nentered the game with one out in the eighth inning and the tying run standing on first base and hit Kennesaw State (8-8, 1-2 CUSA) leadoff hitter with his first pitch to put the tying run in scoring position. The big southpaw took a deep breath, settled in, and set down the next five hitters in a row to earn his first career save and preserve a 4-3 Blue Raider win. The tying runner that got to second base in the eighth was the ninth Owl baserunner that Blue Raider pitching left in scoring position. Between starter\nDavid Horn Jr.\n,\nLanden Burch\nand Kerrigan, Middle Tennessee limited Kennesaw State to a 2-for-13 day with runners in scoring position.\nThe Owls pushed the game's first run across in the first inning but trailed 2-1 after three innings thanks to an RBI from\nNathan Brewer\n, his fifth of the weekend, after\nOwen Nowak\nscored on a failed pickoff throw to first that squirted toward the Blue Raider dugout.\nKennesaw State tacked on two more in the fourth inning on a two out double to lead 3-2 until the bottom of the seventh inning when\nOwen Nowak\ncollected his sixth RBI of the weekend to tie the game and first baseman\nDean O'Neill\ndoubled to straightaway centerfield on a ball that continued to carry in the wind to score\nLayne Akers\nfrom third and give Middle Tennessee the lead at 4-3.\nBurch, who entered the game with the Blue Raiders down a run, allowed just three base runners in two innings to win his fourth game of the season while Kerrigan allowed just one to reach in a five-out save. Horn Jr's 5.1 innings pitched was the longest outing of the year, thus far, for him and he racked up five strikeouts allowing just one earned run in the effort.\nRight fielder\nBrett Rogers\nled the Blue Raiders at the dish, finishing 4-for-4 with a double and a run scored.\nOwen Nowak\ncapped off a productive weekend by combining to go 6-for-12 with six RBIs and five runs scored, two home runs and a stolen base.\nBy the Numbers\n5.1:\ninnings marks the longest outing of the year for\nDavid Horn Jr.\n9:\nOwl runners stranded in scoring position by Blue Raider pitching.\n4:\nhits today for\nBrett Rogers\n, who also scored a run.\nThe Skipper Speaks (\nJerry Meyers\n)\n\"From an offensive standpoint, guys have been able to slow the game down,\" said Middle Tennessee Head Coach\nJerry Meyers\n. \"Playing through adversity, whether at-bat or on the mound, was big. David Horn didn't want to come out of the game when he did because he felt responsible for the jam we were in. Had to pry the ball out of his hand, and same with (Landon) Burch, but we had a better matchup when we took him out with a lefty coming up going to Kerrigan, and he did a really nice job.\"\nPlayer Perspective (LHP\nColin Kerrigan\n)\n\"I was hurt a few times last year and hurt over the summer,\" Kerrigan said. \"It's been nice to come back this year and see all the hard work I put in during rehab from the coaches come together. It's been relieving and exciting. Coach (Meyers) told me to be ready to go today. As soon I got the call, I knew I just needed to keep the routing the same like any other day.\"\n(OF\nBrett Rogers\n)\n\"(With the wind blowing out) it happens a lot where (you can overswing),\" Rogers said. \"During (batting practice), you might hit a ball and see it fly over the fence and think of how bad you want to do it during the game, but (Kennesaw State Starter Nolan Sliver) had good sinking action on his fastball, so I knew I had to stay down through it and not come up, which happens a lot when you try to hit home runs.\"\nUp next\nMiddle Tennessee will play host to Murray State on Tuesday at 4:00 p.m. Coverage will be provided by the Blue Raider Network."
  },
